						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Broken pillar lying near the temple of Banaśaṅkari.</hi></p>						

						<p>Amōghavarsha I—(Undated).</p>						

						<p>This inscription refers itself to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha</hi> and states that <hi rend="bold">Tivuḷara Māramma-Gōsāsi</hi> set up a <hi rend="italic">mēṇṭi</hi> when <hi rend="bold">Inda,</hi> who is described as <hi rend="italic">priya-tanay-ātmaja</hi> of <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha,</hi> is stated to be governing <hi rend="bold">Banavāsi Twelve-thousand.</hi> His wife <hi rend="bold">Gōyindabbe</hi> was administering the village <hi rend="italic">i.e.,</hi> <hi rend="bold">Dēvagēri</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Kaliyamma</hi> was holding the office of <hi rend="italic">nāḻgāmuṇḍu.</hi> The record is engraved in characters of the <hi rend="bold">9th century A.D.</hi> </p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
